WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:04.540
ROMAN NURIK: Hello again,
and welcome to

00:00:04.540 --> 00:00:06.070
Android Design in Action.

00:00:06.070 --> 00:00:06.960
I'm Roman Nurik.

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:08.306
ADAM KOCH: Adam Koch.

00:00:08.306 --> 00:00:10.130
NICK BUTCHER: And
Nick Butcher.

00:00:10.130 --> 00:00:14.010
ROMAN NURIK: And today we're
going to talk about a sleep

00:00:14.010 --> 00:00:16.650
monitor app and backward
compatibility.

00:00:16.650 --> 00:00:19.230
We have a lot of content to get
through today, so we're

00:00:19.230 --> 00:00:23.090
just going to get started
with sleep monitors.

00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:25.660
So the app that we decided
to look at today

00:00:25.660 --> 00:00:29.020
was Sleep as Android.

00:00:29.020 --> 00:00:30.050
It's called Sleep as Android.

00:00:30.050 --> 00:00:32.350
This is one of the apps that was
reviewed on the App Clinic

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:34.390
last Friday by Reto Meier.

00:00:34.390 --> 00:00:37.800
And Nick took a look at this
app in much detail.

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:41.240
And Nick, do you want
to jump into your

00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:43.560
thoughts on Sleep as Android?

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:44.565
NICK BUTCHER: Sure.

00:00:44.565 --> 00:00:47.760
So Sleep as Android is an
application that monitors your

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:50.490
sleep and lets you set an alarm,
so it will wake you up

00:00:50.490 --> 00:00:52.690
at an opportune time when you're
in a very kind of light

00:00:52.690 --> 00:00:54.400
sleep cycle.

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:55.890
It's a very detailed app.

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:58.520
If you take a look at it,
it offers a whole ton of

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:00.850
functionality and configuration
options.

00:01:00.850 --> 00:01:03.090
And you can see that the author
is very responsive to

00:01:03.090 --> 00:01:03.680
the community.

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:06.920
He's put out something like 15
updates in the last couple of

00:01:06.920 --> 00:01:10.340
months alone, which is very,
very responsive.

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:14.090
From a visual point of view,
they have made some effort to

00:01:14.090 --> 00:01:18.990
get towards the Holo
design guidelines.

00:01:18.990 --> 00:01:22.660
But my overall feeling of the
application was that while

00:01:22.660 --> 00:01:25.810
it's very, very functional and
powerful, I found it kind of

00:01:25.810 --> 00:01:29.975
hard to get into and understand
how to operate and

00:01:29.975 --> 00:01:33.680
to prioritize what tasks I
should be doing first and what

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:35.840
information was important.

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:38.940
So if we take a look at
the application here--

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:41.100
this is the first screen you
see when you start the app.

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:44.410
This is where you can create
different alarms, as well as

00:01:44.410 --> 00:01:46.280
there's a prompt to unlock.

00:01:46.280 --> 00:01:48.670
And some of the key
functionality on this screen

00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:52.487
is down there on the bottom
left, kind of like a

00:01:52.487 --> 00:01:54.000
split-action bar, but kind
of not a split-action

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:55.930
bar at the same time.

00:01:55.930 --> 00:01:58.590
And you can see some of the
functionality there is to add

00:01:58.590 --> 00:02:02.370
a new alarm, start the actual
sleep-tracking mode, to see

00:02:02.370 --> 00:02:07.210
some statistics of your previous
night's sleep.

00:02:07.210 --> 00:02:09.550
So, since we're short for time,
should we go straight

00:02:09.550 --> 00:02:15.790
into the redesign and see
what we cooked up?

00:02:15.790 --> 00:02:18.860
So here, you can see
we've done--

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:21.720
it's not a huge departure, but
we tried to apply some of the

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:23.280
Holo look and feel to
the application.

00:02:23.280 --> 00:02:25.360
So straight off there's a
standard action bar giving

00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:28.430
that that sense of where you
are, and a common place to

00:02:28.430 --> 00:02:29.680
look for some of the actions.

00:02:32.010 --> 00:02:33.420
I felt like we had to reorganize
some of the

00:02:33.420 --> 00:02:35.640
functionality a little bit,
because this main screen,

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:39.030
while it offered the alarms,
there's a lot of functionality

00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:40.510
kind of hanging off sub-screens,
as well.

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:43.440
And I felt like this app has
two main purposes, which is

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:45.280
setting alarms for waking up
at the right time, and for

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:47.800
monitoring your sleep
and seeing how that

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:48.890
sleep pattern is going.

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:52.250
So I wanted to float those
right up as your primary

00:02:52.250 --> 00:02:55.620
options into these two main
tabs, here, these Alarms and

00:02:55.620 --> 00:02:57.550
Stats tabs.

00:02:57.550 --> 00:03:01.640
As you can see, we've also
really, really emphasized the

00:03:01.640 --> 00:03:03.810
Track Sleep button.

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:06.120
So instead of just a little
button at the bottom with

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:09.100
equal, fair weighting toward
the other options, it's now

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:11.940
this gigantic purple button.

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:16.250
And finally, a little note on
the coloring and the palette.

00:03:16.250 --> 00:03:19.570
I found some of the green
highlights to be grabbing your

00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:23.080
focus, saying, look at me,
I'm a divider, which felt

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:25.530
slightly off to me.

00:03:25.530 --> 00:03:28.370
So we readdressed the palette
a little bit here.

00:03:28.370 --> 00:03:32.515
It's taking quite a lot of
cues from the stock alarm

00:03:32.515 --> 00:03:35.590
clock in the latest version of
Android for two reasons.

00:03:35.590 --> 00:03:37.030
Firstly, I like it.

00:03:37.030 --> 00:03:39.700
I think it's a that beautiful
app-- might be controversial,

00:03:39.700 --> 00:03:41.130
not everyone thinks so.

00:03:41.130 --> 00:03:44.050
But also, it is offering
slightly similarly

00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:45.650
functionality, so it's
helping to bootstrap

00:03:45.650 --> 00:03:46.710
these as mental model.

00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:50.415
A lot of the user interface
elements we've used look the

00:03:50.415 --> 00:03:52.172
same as from the stock
alarm clock app.

00:03:52.172 --> 00:03:53.990
So hopefully it can get started
with this application

00:03:53.990 --> 00:03:55.040
a bit quicker.

00:03:55.040 --> 00:03:55.420
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:58.460
One thing I wanted to mention
about the color scheme, the

00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:03.230
switch from these neon green
to a neon violet.

00:04:03.230 --> 00:04:08.570
I guess it's the violet that's
in the Android Design official

00:04:08.570 --> 00:04:10.230
color palette.

00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:13.600
I think that it's just a little
less in your face.

00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:15.740
It's still very much
an accent color.

00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:18.275
It's not like a dull gray
or a dull blue,

00:04:18.275 --> 00:04:19.730
where it's more muted.

00:04:19.730 --> 00:04:21.720
But it's a little easier
on the eyes.

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:24.440
And I think you can even
probably go even one shade

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:25.670
darker, if you want.

00:04:25.670 --> 00:04:27.970
On some devices, it
may be too bright.

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:32.560
But I think it's just much
easier to look at the screen

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:34.780
and not be overwhelmed
immediately.

00:04:34.780 --> 00:04:34.900
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah.

00:04:34.900 --> 00:04:36.980
One of the thing that I wanted
to say is that this is one of

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:40.070
the last things you'll look
at before you go to sleep.

00:04:40.070 --> 00:04:42.330
If you're about to go to bed,
you're going to hit Sleep.

00:04:42.330 --> 00:04:45.232
So normally, for this kind of
app, I would immediately want

00:04:45.232 --> 00:04:48.100
to change it to a
light palette.

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:50.140
For most apps I think a light
palette is generally a good

00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:50.920
starting point.

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:52.985
But, for this app, because you
didn't want to have that

00:04:52.985 --> 00:04:54.780
feeling of you're [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:57.460
and you turn your phone, and
suddenly, you're kind of

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:00.370
blinded by intensity.

00:05:00.370 --> 00:05:03.235
So I tried to keep the tones
quite mute to try and ease

00:05:03.235 --> 00:05:05.510
that kind of transition,
really.

00:05:05.510 --> 00:05:07.160
ADAM KOCH: In terms of
navigation, I like how you've

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:11.890
split Stats and Alarms into the
top-level tabs there, and

00:05:11.890 --> 00:05:15.990
removing it from the faux
split-action bar that was in

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:19.070
the previous version, leaving
the two main actions that are

00:05:19.070 --> 00:05:21.260
visible there-- the Track
Sleep and the Add.

00:05:25.630 --> 00:05:28.790
NICK BUTCHER: I found a point
on the before shot.

00:05:28.790 --> 00:05:30.290
You can see there's a little
bug droid figure

00:05:30.290 --> 00:05:32.180
in the bottom corner.

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:34.570
And his state changes depending
on how close it is

00:05:34.570 --> 00:05:36.350
to you having to go to bed.

00:05:36.350 --> 00:05:39.110
So right now, it's the daytime,
and he's got a

00:05:39.110 --> 00:05:40.700
[INAUDIBLE] in front
of him or whatever.

00:05:40.700 --> 00:05:42.450
But as he gets close to night,
he starts brushing his

00:05:42.450 --> 00:05:43.840
teeth and so on.

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:46.360
And while I think that's
useful and fun--

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:47.150
I do really like that--

00:05:47.150 --> 00:05:49.340
I do find sometimes including
a bug droid in your

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:51.840
application or even Android or
Droid in the name of the

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:55.080
application is kind of
lazy and amateurish.

00:05:55.080 --> 00:05:57.660
It doesn't really shout, this
is a fully professional

00:05:57.660 --> 00:05:58.110
application.

00:05:58.110 --> 00:06:00.470
I've thought through
the interaction.

00:06:00.470 --> 00:06:02.820
So I tried to incorporate the
same elements using Same

00:06:02.820 --> 00:06:04.620
Difference.

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:06.170
So if you can see on the
aftershot, very subtly,

00:06:06.170 --> 00:06:10.120
there's a number of sleepy Z's
in the background to the

00:06:10.120 --> 00:06:11.380
application.

00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:15.000
The idea here being as you get
closer to bedtime, more of

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:17.642
them start coming out from the
Track Sleep button or you

00:06:17.642 --> 00:06:19.260
could have them subtly
animate in some ways.

00:06:19.260 --> 00:06:22.020
It's very, very subtle here, but
it's trying to convey the

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:27.220
same kind of information, but in
a slightly more subtle way.

00:06:27.220 --> 00:06:27.610
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:06:27.610 --> 00:06:32.020
And we also did a job on
changing the icons.

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:36.050
So we shifted the icon from
being a sleeping, cute bug

00:06:36.050 --> 00:06:38.330
droid to something
very generic.

00:06:38.330 --> 00:06:40.900
This is just a very generic
icon, but, again, something

00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:44.330
that is a little more
recognizable and something

00:06:44.330 --> 00:06:46.570
that is a little more
unique to the app.

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:49.950
NICK BUTCHER: Cool.

00:06:49.950 --> 00:06:50.300
[INAUDIBLE].

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:51.666
ROMAN NURIK: Should we move
on to the next screen?

00:06:51.666 --> 00:06:54.000
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:55.950
All righty.

00:06:55.950 --> 00:06:58.575
So next up.

00:06:58.575 --> 00:07:00.385
The next one of the major
functions I thought this app

00:07:00.385 --> 00:07:03.660
does is give you lots of
information about how you have

00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:06.780
been sleeping, almost too
much information.

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:09.380
So if we touch the graph, like
on the bottom left, you get to

00:07:09.380 --> 00:07:11.910
the subsequent screen here with
a number of options here.

00:07:11.910 --> 00:07:15.020
So we've picked out the Stat
screen here, which can have a

00:07:15.020 --> 00:07:16.580
very, very long table.

00:07:16.580 --> 00:07:20.780
And this is just and a small
sampling of information,

00:07:20.780 --> 00:07:23.380
because I hadn't been running
the app for very long.

00:07:23.380 --> 00:07:24.970
If you look at the developer's
screenshots on the place

00:07:24.970 --> 00:07:26.740
though, you can see this
can be a massive table.

00:07:26.740 --> 00:07:29.300
And while it gives you some
average stats, it's summed up

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:31.180
over all time.

00:07:31.180 --> 00:07:34.210
Now, I tried to readdress this
and think, what do I really

00:07:34.210 --> 00:07:34.615
care about?

00:07:34.615 --> 00:07:38.220
I probably only care about the
last week's stats, like

00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:41.220
anything that's older than that
probably doesn't really

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:44.985
have much bearing on how I feel
my sleep has been going.

00:07:44.985 --> 00:07:46.530
What happened two months
ago isn't really

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:48.090
relevant any longer.

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:52.080
So what I've done with this
screen is I've tried to

00:07:52.080 --> 00:07:53.830
provide these summary stats.

00:07:53.830 --> 00:07:56.870
So the most important thing to
me is a summary of this week,

00:07:56.870 --> 00:08:00.170
how have I been doing for the
last, say, seven days or

00:08:00.170 --> 00:08:03.120
whenever the start of the week
in your calendar starts from.

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:05.090
And so we've pulled out some
summary statistics, and those

00:08:05.090 --> 00:08:06.240
are big and bold.

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:09.450
And it uses color to signify
whether you are close to your

00:08:09.450 --> 00:08:12.410
target average length of sleep
per night or whether you're

00:08:12.410 --> 00:08:14.060
building up a sleep debt.

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:17.830
So here, we can see we're using
orange for OK-ish, blue

00:08:17.830 --> 00:08:21.030
for yeah, you're doing well, or
red for warning, you're not

00:08:21.030 --> 00:08:21.860
getting enough sleep.

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:24.660
So instantly, when I look at
this, I get this quick,

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:27.350
scannable screen which tells
me what's going on.

00:08:27.350 --> 00:08:27.600
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:29.890
You can see that on Tuesday,
you, for some reason, didn't

00:08:29.890 --> 00:08:30.440
sleep very well.

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:34.328
Maybe you were out on the town
the night before, or

00:08:34.328 --> 00:08:35.568
something like that.

00:08:35.568 --> 00:08:36.560
NICK BUTCHER: Too
many Christmas

00:08:36.560 --> 00:08:38.549
parties at the moment.

00:08:38.549 --> 00:08:42.110
So, we've consciously demoted
a lot of information.

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:44.140
So if you look at the before,
there's other tabs for noise

00:08:44.140 --> 00:08:47.320
and graphs, as well as some kind
of store, as well, which

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:49.730
didn't seem to be worthy
of being a

00:08:49.730 --> 00:08:51.230
top-level information item.

00:08:51.230 --> 00:08:53.680
It was kind of like adding
noise, and making it harder

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:55.750
for me to realize what
was really important.

00:08:55.750 --> 00:08:59.590
So we've really simplified it
down to these few items, and

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:02.160
we let you roll the whole week
up and down, if you want to

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:06.210
turn it into a summary or drill
down into each one.

00:09:06.210 --> 00:09:08.490
We still think this
information's interesting, for

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:09.750
those people who
want it though.

00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:12.820
So the idea here is that you can
tap on each of the days.

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:16.530
You can then go forward into a
subsequent screen, which is

00:09:16.530 --> 00:09:18.430
going to give you details about
that one night's sleep

00:09:18.430 --> 00:09:20.332
that you've tracked.

00:09:20.332 --> 00:09:21.510
ROMAN NURIK: Cool.

00:09:21.510 --> 00:09:28.940
NICK BUTCHER: So here, on the
next slide, instead of having

00:09:28.940 --> 00:09:33.215
this whole roll of graphs--

00:09:33.215 --> 00:09:35.870
that kind of view of all the
different days as a graph

00:09:35.870 --> 00:09:37.170
didn't really tell me much.

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:38.870
I didn't find that
very glanceable.

00:09:38.870 --> 00:09:40.630
You couldn't really look at it
and say, oh, that was a good

00:09:40.630 --> 00:09:42.360
night, oh, that was
a bad night.

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:44.190
But the graphs themselves
are quite cool.

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:46.390
So we demoted them down
to a detail screen.

00:09:46.390 --> 00:09:48.870
So if you touched each of the
line items from the previous

00:09:48.870 --> 00:09:51.320
screen, you get through to sleep
details that will tell

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:54.900
you how long you actually slept
for, how long of that

00:09:54.900 --> 00:09:57.590
was in deep sleep, what
percentage, and give you that

00:09:57.590 --> 00:10:00.720
really nice graph showing
you exactly what

00:10:00.720 --> 00:10:01.420
the night was like.

00:10:01.420 --> 00:10:02.480
That's where there's
a [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:04.790
information can capture when
you record your sleep--

00:10:04.790 --> 00:10:07.620
like a rating or a comment on
how good a night it was.

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:10.280
So these are really details
that truly change the

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:13.452
information hierarchy and
can put these down to

00:10:13.452 --> 00:10:14.591
a subsequent screen.

00:10:14.591 --> 00:10:15.020
[INAUDIBLE].

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:17.920
ROMAN NURIK: I think it was
just a great job, just

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:21.820
splitting up a very, very
complex screen-- a complex

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:24.590
screen that has good
data, but it's just

00:10:24.590 --> 00:10:26.730
not as easy to consume.

00:10:26.730 --> 00:10:30.090
And showing you something that's
letting you really look

00:10:30.090 --> 00:10:33.920
at the content, or one specific
piece of content, the

00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:36.390
specific day, and seeing
all the details on it.

00:10:36.390 --> 00:10:40.070
I think it's just a good
combination of different types

00:10:40.070 --> 00:10:43.880
of pieces of the content, like
a graph, some averages, some

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:45.090
data like that.

00:10:45.090 --> 00:10:49.160
Potentially allowing the user to
provide a comment, or even

00:10:49.160 --> 00:10:50.230
providing a recommendation.

00:10:50.230 --> 00:10:55.160
Like maybe you should wear
something or sleep stiller.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:55.620
Who knows?

00:10:55.620 --> 00:10:58.573
I know nothing about sleeping
medication or

00:10:58.573 --> 00:10:58.950
anything like that.

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:02.680
But giving the user all these
different types of components

00:11:02.680 --> 00:11:05.680
to their one night of sleep is
a really interesting and

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:07.380
unique way to present that.

00:11:07.380 --> 00:11:07.830
ADAM KOCH: Yeah.

00:11:07.830 --> 00:11:09.695
Personally, I really like the
typography that you've used

00:11:09.695 --> 00:11:12.500
here, Nick, on both this screen
and the other screen.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:14.927
It just really brings out the
important information, and

00:11:14.927 --> 00:11:16.550
plus the coloring
really helps.

00:11:16.550 --> 00:11:21.410
It helps you glance at it
and see what's going on.

00:11:21.410 --> 00:11:21.930
NICK BUTCHER: Cool.

00:11:21.930 --> 00:11:26.170
And there's one final redesign
idea we had for this

00:11:26.170 --> 00:11:26.910
application.

00:11:26.910 --> 00:11:29.940
And that's to take advantage
of a cool new feature in

00:11:29.940 --> 00:11:33.410
Android 4.2 called Daydreams.

00:11:33.410 --> 00:11:36.360
So for those of you who might
not be aware, Daydreams is

00:11:36.360 --> 00:11:38.160
like a screensaver
functionality.

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:41.660
So you can set up a Daydream to
say that when my device is

00:11:41.660 --> 00:11:44.590
docked or charging, kick
over into this--

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:46.800
kind of like a screensaver.

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:48.570
So what I thought would be
really, really cool is rather

00:11:48.570 --> 00:11:51.917
than having to manually go into
the application and start

00:11:51.917 --> 00:11:55.840
it to track you sleeping,
it would be awesome if--

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:57.950
just the fact that, I guess,
most people like me probably

00:11:57.950 --> 00:12:01.130
plug their phone in at night
so it's charging overnight.

00:12:01.130 --> 00:12:05.740
So just doing that is enough
to say kick off a Daydream,

00:12:05.740 --> 00:12:08.630
which will then start
tracking your sleep.

00:12:08.630 --> 00:12:10.480
I imagine you'd probably put
some logic in there if it's in

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:12.310
the middle of the day, or
something like this.

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:13.990
You wouldn't actually
kick off Daydream.

00:12:13.990 --> 00:12:16.910
But just the act of plugging in
the device and putting it

00:12:16.910 --> 00:12:19.490
down on your bed could then kick
off the functionality.

00:12:19.490 --> 00:12:24.840
So I really find it's a bit of
a burden on the user to have

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:27.210
to go into this application
every night and

00:12:27.210 --> 00:12:28.340
remember to do it.

00:12:28.340 --> 00:12:29.290
Hit the Start button,
hit the Stop button.

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:31.710
Remember to do that
in the morning.

00:12:31.710 --> 00:12:34.490
So anything you can do to
automate that process I think

00:12:34.490 --> 00:12:37.430
is going to make the
user more regular.

00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:39.170
They're going to keep on using
it and see the value of their

00:12:39.170 --> 00:12:40.140
application.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:43.060
So I thought a Daydream might
be a cool way to do that.

00:12:43.060 --> 00:12:43.225
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:12:43.225 --> 00:12:45.940
It's just another way to step
up the level of, or the

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:49.080
feeling of, magic in this
app, where, if you can

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:52.160
automatically track these
things, then do it.

00:12:52.160 --> 00:12:56.980
So before 9:00 PM, 10:00 PM,
if it turns on, or if your

00:12:56.980 --> 00:13:00.930
phone goes idle, maybe you
just show a clock.

00:13:00.930 --> 00:13:04.810
It's fairly easy to just create
a simple clock Daydream

00:13:04.810 --> 00:13:07.010
that just shows the current
time and the current date.

00:13:07.010 --> 00:13:10.420
But then after a certain point,
it kicks into kind of

00:13:10.420 --> 00:13:12.070
tracking mode and
shows the clock.

00:13:12.070 --> 00:13:17.150
And maybe this is a way to play
like soothing sounds in

00:13:17.150 --> 00:13:20.170
the background or something,
as you're sleeping.

00:13:20.170 --> 00:13:23.890
So since this app is already
doing all this data capture,

00:13:23.890 --> 00:13:26.340
maybe it can use that
intelligently to even improve

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:30.400
your sleep as you're sleeping,
maybe by playing sounds or

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:31.210
