00:15:50.336 --> 00:15:52.776
We'll wait.

00:15:52.776 --> 00:15:53.550
And we're back.

00:15:53.550 --> 00:15:54.240
ADAM KOCH: Let's move on.

00:15:54.240 --> 00:15:54.470
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:15:54.470 --> 00:15:55.650
We do have a lot to cover.

00:15:55.650 --> 00:15:58.640
So backward compatibility.

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:01.490
The way we view backward
compatibility is that for each

00:16:01.490 --> 00:16:03.960
screen in your app-- and you
could extend this to your

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:06.400
entire app or just an
individual widget--

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:10.060
for each screen, visual styling
and the behavior,

00:16:10.060 --> 00:16:14.570
basically visual and interaction
design, can

00:16:14.570 --> 00:16:20.970
operate along a spectrum of how
close it is to the primary

00:16:20.970 --> 00:16:21.930
version of the app.

00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:26.700
So for example, and if I have an
app design for Android 4.0

00:16:26.700 --> 00:16:31.350
and above, and I have Holo
elements in there, on earlier

00:16:31.350 --> 00:16:35.060
versions, on Android 2.3,
Gingerbread, Froyo, whatever,

00:16:35.060 --> 00:16:39.070
you can make a choice of either
taking that Holo design

00:16:39.070 --> 00:16:41.070
or your completely
custom design and

00:16:41.070 --> 00:16:43.070
using it on that device.

00:16:43.070 --> 00:16:45.260
Or you can kind of
say whatever the

00:16:45.260 --> 00:16:47.840
device default is--

00:16:47.840 --> 00:16:50.280
for example, for check boxes
on Gingerbread, they were

00:16:50.280 --> 00:16:52.760
green instead of blue--

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:54.560
in some devices back
then, it was like

00:16:54.560 --> 00:16:56.220
blue, red or whatever.

00:16:56.220 --> 00:17:00.250
You can make the choice that I
should use a device default,

00:17:00.250 --> 00:17:02.060
or you could just choose
something in the middle.

00:17:02.060 --> 00:17:07.500
So usually it's a little harder
to make everything Holo

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:09.900
back to Gingerbread and Froyo.

00:17:09.900 --> 00:17:13.310
It's very, very easy
for developers to

00:17:13.310 --> 00:17:15.530
use the device defaults.

00:17:15.530 --> 00:17:18.640
And then this hybrid is
somewhere in the middle.

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:21.114
So the hybrid solution--

00:17:21.114 --> 00:17:23.260
you have to be kind of
careful about it.

00:17:23.260 --> 00:17:25.300
It can still really work, and
we'll show you guys in the

00:17:25.300 --> 00:17:28.860
screenshots coming up that
hybrid UIs, where some

00:17:28.860 --> 00:17:32.210
components are Holo and some
components are using the

00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:36.480
device default styling,
they can work.

00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:38.490
So we'll show a couple
of examples of those.

00:17:38.490 --> 00:17:43.270
But this is really how we see
the way you decide on a

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:44.290
backward compatibility
strategy.

00:17:44.290 --> 00:17:46.860
You kind of pick somewhere
along the spectrum.

00:17:46.860 --> 00:17:49.180
And depending on where you
choose, you need to work with

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:50.000
your developers on this.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.060
But depending on where you
choose, that will change the

00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:56.900
amount of effort involved for
developers, and certainly it

00:17:56.900 --> 00:17:58.250
will change the final outcome.

00:17:58.250 --> 00:18:03.050
But just be aware that these are
the different options, and

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:04.740
there's really no correct
choice, I'd say.

00:18:04.740 --> 00:18:07.940
Like I said before, you can do
it correctly, you can do it

00:18:07.940 --> 00:18:11.030
right using any one of these
different options.

00:18:11.030 --> 00:18:12.892
It's really up to you to make
sure that it just works well.

00:18:12.892 --> 00:18:13.260
ADAM KOCH: Yeah.

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:14.530
It's really just a
trade-off between

00:18:14.530 --> 00:18:15.320
these different options.

00:18:15.320 --> 00:18:17.240
Like there's more effort
involved on the left side of

00:18:17.240 --> 00:18:21.460
the spectrum, but you'll have
a more consistent look.

00:18:21.460 --> 00:18:23.721
On the right side, it can still
work, as we'll show you

00:18:23.721 --> 00:18:26.410
in the screenshots shortly.

00:18:26.410 --> 00:18:27.103
NICK BUTCHER: A bit
more effort.

00:18:27.103 --> 00:18:27.830
There's some tools out
there to help.

00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:28.350
ROMAN NURIK: Absolutely.

00:18:28.350 --> 00:18:30.520
And we'll talk about the tools
out there that are more

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:33.830
relevant to the developers
and designers, but still,

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:36.010
definitely, there is stuff
out there to help.

00:18:36.010 --> 00:18:39.520
So having said that, Holo--

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:42.185
a lot of people ask
us-- is Holo for

00:18:42.185 --> 00:18:43.970
Android 4.0 and above?

00:18:43.970 --> 00:18:46.390
In the end, should I even try
to use Holo in earlier

00:18:46.390 --> 00:18:48.240
versions of the platform?

00:18:48.240 --> 00:18:49.320
And our answer is yes.

00:18:49.320 --> 00:18:53.250
Holo is not designed just for
the latest devices out there.

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:57.060
Holo is really designed for all
people, for all humans.

00:18:57.060 --> 00:19:00.230
It's really a design language
for human-computer

00:19:00.230 --> 00:19:03.400
interaction, not just
human-Android 4.0 Plus

00:19:03.400 --> 00:19:05.440
interaction.

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:07.910
It can work everywhere.

00:19:07.910 --> 00:19:10.180
Obviously, it takes some effort
to make it work, but

00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:13.020
again, as a designer, you to
think of it less as the

00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:15.200
styling of Android 4.0,
and really as

00:19:15.200 --> 00:19:17.850
the identity of Android.

00:19:17.850 --> 00:19:18.980
So that's an important
point to make.

00:19:18.980 --> 00:19:22.620
Another is that the core
experience across all

00:19:22.620 --> 00:19:24.260
platforms should really
be consistent.

00:19:24.260 --> 00:19:27.480
You shouldn't really have to
design an entirely separate

00:19:27.480 --> 00:19:31.940
app for Gingerbread and for
Ice Cream Sandwich.

00:19:31.940 --> 00:19:35.730
So things like the action bar,
those should be visible and

00:19:35.730 --> 00:19:37.590
persistent across all devices.

00:19:37.590 --> 00:19:41.290
You shouldn't switch into a
completely different UI on

00:19:41.290 --> 00:19:42.910
earlier versions just
because there's no

00:19:42.910 --> 00:19:44.130
built-in framework component.

00:19:44.130 --> 00:19:46.190
And, again, we'll
talk about that.

00:19:46.190 --> 00:19:49.420
So things like layouts, the core
layouts, the navigation--

00:19:49.420 --> 00:19:51.230
like swiping between tabs--

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:52.320
and the core interactions--

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:58.480
like the basic way you choose
a contact, for example.

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:00.230
Those should really behave
the same across

00:20:00.230 --> 00:20:02.810
different OS versions.

00:20:02.810 --> 00:20:07.410
And I think that for design--
and the last point is really

00:20:07.410 --> 00:20:09.380
more about developers--

00:20:09.380 --> 00:20:10.710
but be opportunistic.

00:20:10.710 --> 00:20:14.530
Beyond the core experience, the
core navigation, really,

00:20:14.530 --> 00:20:17.660
the core feel of the app, like
the individual check boxes,

00:20:17.660 --> 00:20:21.050
and the spinners, and
things like that, be

00:20:21.050 --> 00:20:22.000
opportunistic about it.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:25.100
Make sure that nothing looks
really bad, obviously, but be

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:25.750
opportunistic.

00:20:25.750 --> 00:20:29.330
And don't put yourself in a
position where you must have

00:20:29.330 --> 00:20:31.520
everything pixel-perfect,
because that's

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:32.550
just a losing battle.

00:20:32.550 --> 00:20:34.960
It's going to take too much
time, and you're going to lose

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:37.460
focus from what's really
important, and that is the

00:20:37.460 --> 00:20:40.190
core experience of the app.

00:20:40.190 --> 00:20:43.250
So before we go on, any
other points, guys?

00:20:43.250 --> 00:20:46.146
About these three?

00:20:46.146 --> 00:20:46.530
NICK BUTCHER: Nope.

00:20:46.530 --> 00:20:47.290
ADAM KOCH: Let's go.

00:20:47.290 --> 00:20:47.560
ROMAN NURIK: Solid.

00:20:47.560 --> 00:20:47.740
Let's go.

00:20:47.740 --> 00:20:49.290
ADAM KOCH: Let's do it.

00:20:49.290 --> 00:20:51.070
ROMAN NURIK: Another thing to
mention-- this is more on the

00:20:51.070 --> 00:20:52.280
tactical side.

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:54.450
So one of the big differences,
and you'll see this in

00:20:54.450 --> 00:20:58.050
screenshots, between Android 4.0
and Android 2.3 and such

00:20:58.050 --> 00:21:01.020
is the topography,
is the font.

00:21:01.020 --> 00:21:05.150
So Roboto is the default on
Android 4.0 and higher, and

00:21:05.150 --> 00:21:08.420
Droid Sans was the default
everywhere else.

00:21:08.420 --> 00:21:11.190
So this is one area where you
really shouldn't try to just

00:21:11.190 --> 00:21:16.190
take Roboto and use it
everywhere on Android 2.3.

00:21:16.190 --> 00:21:19.920
The reason being that users
are really accustomed to

00:21:19.920 --> 00:21:23.200
seeing-- like their eyes almost
expect to read text in

00:21:23.200 --> 00:21:26.320
a certain way on their device,
and so you should really just

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:27.800
use the system default font.

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:29.620
The good thing is that for
designers, when you're

00:21:29.620 --> 00:21:34.193
planning out the widths of your
elements and things, you

00:21:34.193 --> 00:21:38.070
have to think, obviously, how
many characters will fit in

00:21:38.070 --> 00:21:39.780
this line or in this
UI widget.

00:21:39.780 --> 00:21:41.750
And the good thing is that
Roboto and Droid Sans are

00:21:41.750 --> 00:21:44.370
metrics-compatible, meaning
that if you take the same

00:21:44.370 --> 00:21:47.630
piece of text in Roboto and
Droid Sans on an Android 2.3

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:50.470
device and an Android 4.0
device, you'll notice that

00:21:50.470 --> 00:21:52.720
they're pretty much
the same width.

00:21:52.720 --> 00:21:56.090
So what's more important here
is things like translations,

00:21:56.090 --> 00:21:59.980
where, for example, the German
version or the German strings

00:21:59.980 --> 00:22:01.810
for something will cause
things to be

00:22:01.810 --> 00:22:03.110
really, really wide.

00:22:03.110 --> 00:22:06.750
That's more important to think
about than just saying, oh, I

00:22:06.750 --> 00:22:08.920
need to choose the
right font here.

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:11.770
So be more aware of that than
just the difference between

00:22:11.770 --> 00:22:15.650
Droid Sans and Roboto in
English, for example.

00:22:15.650 --> 00:22:17.160
And then also--

00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:19.050
this is, again, more
for tactics--

00:22:19.050 --> 00:22:22.670
but in your process, it's really
important for designers

00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:26.170
to participate in the
device-testing process.

00:22:26.170 --> 00:22:30.330
So usually, you'll have a QA
team or maybe a developer that

00:22:30.330 --> 00:22:34.200
has a whole bunch of devices,
and they're kind of testing

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:36.960
